info:
Manage Jupyter servers available to the flow.

It allows one server/kernel/session to be running globally (within node-red).
At the moment, it does not allow a connection to an existing server, but it should be easy to implement.

The allowed inputs are:
 1. "start": Simply start a server, kernel and session if not already started;
 2. "restart": Restart kernel/session (useful if something is wrong, without the need of messing with the server);
 3. "stop": Stop the running server. If for some reason a running server was "lost" to the flow (e.g.: after a crash), it **WILL NOT BE STOPPED**;
 4. "stop all": Stop all running servers on the machine. **USE CAUTION WITH THIS ONE!**

There is a status indicator that runs at a 1 second interval. If the flow is connected to a server, it will be indicated.

It doesn't return anything useful.

